  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Jehovah had seen the affliction of His people, had heard their cry under their taskmasters, and had come down (ירד, vid., ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 11:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") to deliver them out of the hand of the Egyptians, and to bring them up to a good and broad land, to the place of the Canaanites; and He was about to send Moses to Pharaoh to bring them forth. The land to which the Israelites were to be taken up is called a \"good\" land, on account of its great fertility (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 8:7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".), and a \"broad\" land, in contrast with the confinement and oppression of the Israelites in Egypt. The epithet \"good\" is then explained by the expression, \"a land flowing with milk and honey\" (זבת, a participle of זוּב in the construct state; vid., Ges. 135); a proverbial description of the extraordinary fertility and loveliness of the land of Canaan (cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 3:17",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 13:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 16:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", etc.). Milk and honey are the simplest and choicest productions of a land abounding in grass and flowers, and were found in Palestine in great abundance even when it was in a desolate condition (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Isaiah 7:15",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Isaiah 7:22",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; see my Comm. on ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Joshua 5:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). The epithet broad is explained by an enumeration of the six tribes inhabiting the country at that time (cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 10:15",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". and ",
        "children": []
